Background

In this handout, we consider several simple differential equations that characterize growth. We then consider the solution of this differential equation.

Constant (Linear) Growth

\(dN/dt\) Form

\[\frac{dN}{dt} = k\]

implies

\[N = kt + C\]

\(dy/dx\) Form

\[\frac{dy}{dx} = k\]

implies

\[y = kx + C\]

Exponential Growth

\(dN/dt\) Form

\[\frac{dN}{dt} = N\]

implies

\[N = e^t + C\]

\(dy/dx\) Form

\[\frac{dy}{dx} = y\]

implies

\[y = e^x + C\]

Logistic Growth

\(dN/dt\) Form

\[\frac{dN}{dt} = N \left(1 - \frac{N}{N_0} \right)\]

implies

implies

\[y = N_0 \left( \frac{e^t}{1 + e^t} \right)\]

\(dy/dx\) Form

\[\frac{dy}{dx} = y \left(1 - y \right)\] implies

\[y = \frac{e^x}{1 + e^x}\]
